<body lang=EN-US style='tab-interval:.5in'>

<div class=Section1>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>Psych
421<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>Methods
of Psychological Inquiry<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>David
Allbritton<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>Homework
4: Data Description<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>50
points<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>In
this assignment you will create tables and graphs for a set of hypothetical
(fake) data.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The methods you use will
be similar to those demonstrated in class.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>In addition, you will do exercise 6.1 in the textbook.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Your answers are to be turned in along with
the rest of this assignment.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>After
doing exercise 6.1 in the text, follow these instructions to select a sample
data set and create tables and graphs describing it.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>It is suggested but not required that you use graph paper for all
graphs.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>If you do not use graph paper,
make sure the intervals on your graph are clearly marked and lined.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><span style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<ol style='margin-top:0in' start=1 type=1>
 <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level1 lfo3;tab-stops:list .5in'><span
     style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>Select 10
     &quot;subjects&quot; at random from the population dataset on p. 418 of
     your text.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Use the random number
     table on p. 416 in <i>exactly</i> the following way to select your 10
     subjects.<o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <ol style='margin-top:0in' start=1 type=a>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level2 lfo3;tab-stops:list 1.0in'><span
      style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>Counting up from the
      bottom of the table, start on the left end of the 10<sup>th</sup> line
      (the line that begins &quot;97262&quot;)<o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level2 lfo3;tab-stops:list 1.0in'><span
      style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>Interpret the first 2
      digits as a 2 digit number (97).<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
      </span>Mark through these 2 digits with a pencil.<span
      style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Look for the corresponding number in
      the first column of the dataset on p. 418 (labeled &quot;ID&quot;).<span
      style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>If it exists, circle it.<span
      style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>If not, simply proceed to the next
      step.<o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level2 lfo3;tab-stops:list 1.0in'><span
      style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>Interpret the next 2
      digits (26) as a 2-digit number, and repeat the steps in (b).<span
      style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level2 lfo3;tab-stops:list 1.0in'><span
      style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>Continue until you have
      circled 10 ID numbers on p. 418.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
      </span>If you reach the end of the line in the random number table,
      continue from the left on the next line below it.<o:p></o:p></span></li>
 </ol>
 <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level1 lfo3;tab-stops:list .5in'><span
     style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>Create a data summary
     sheet for these 10 &quot;subjects&quot; using the information from the
     following columns on p. 418.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
     </span>Pretend that the data is from an experiment on bystander
     intervention in which the researchers wanted to see how long it took a
     participant to get up to help someone who had fallen down (the
     &quot;victim&quot;) depending on how many observers were present and how
     far away the victim was.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The
     variables we will pretend these columns correspond to are given in
     parenthesis.<o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <ol style='margin-top:0in' start=1 type=a>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level2 lfo3;tab-stops:list 1.0in'><span
      style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>ID (subject number)<o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level2 lfo3;tab-stops:list 1.0in'><span
      style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>Sex<o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level2 lfo3;tab-stops:list 1.0in'><span
      style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>B (distance in feet
      between the participant and the victim)<o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level2 lfo3;tab-stops:list 1.0in'><span
      style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>F (number of seconds
      before the participant got up to help) <o:p></o:p></span></li>
  <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level2 lfo3;tab-stops:list 1.0in'><span
      style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>G (number of observers
      present)<br style='mso-special-character:line-break'>
      <![if !supportLineBreakNewLine]><br style='mso-special-character:line-break'>
      <![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></li>
 </ol>
 <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level1 lfo3;tab-stops:list .5in'><span
     style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>Identify the dependent
     variable and independent variable(s).<o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level1 lfo3;tab-stops:list .5in'><span
     style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>Draw a histogram for the
     dependent variable scores.<o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level1 lfo3;tab-stops:list .5in'><span
     style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>Draw a scattergram using
     (F) and (G) as the variables.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>If
     one of them is the DV, use the appropriate (customary) axis for that
     variable.<o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level1 lfo3;tab-stops:list .5in'><span
     style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>Create a table that
     includes &quot;sex&quot;, &quot;distance in feet between the participant
     and the victim&quot;, and the DV.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span><i>You
     are not required to calculate the actual means for the entries in this
     table</i> - just put an “X” where each number would go in the table for
     now.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The point of this assignment
     is to get the <u>form</u> of the table right and put the labels in the
     right places.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>We will discuss how
     to do the necessary calculations later.<o:p></o:p></span></li>
 <li class=MsoNormal style='mso-list:l0 level1 lfo3;tab-stops:list .5in'><span
     style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:6.0pt'>What kind of graph would
     you use to display the data from the table in #6? (name it).<span
     style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span><o:p></o:p></span></li>
</ol>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]>&nbsp;<![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

